<subSubSection id="70E51A85FF8D255AFF4BA9D6A973CAE9" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph id="3840490EFF8D255AFF4BA9D6A864CB6E" blockId="18.[151,1437,635,1563]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFF4BA9D6AD94CDE2" bold="true" box="[199,419,701,728]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Description. Male.</emphasis>
Whole fly as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFDCCA9D5AE97CDE2" box="[576,672,702,728]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–117" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[249,1326,189,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[241,1346,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 110–117. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 110, whole fly; 111, frons; 112, detail of frons; 113, postpedicels to proboscis; 114, tergite 5 to tip of abdomen; 115, left face of epandrium; 116, left face of hypandrium and penis complex; 117, right face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573394/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 110</figureCitation>
. Frons as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFC9CA9D5AF5ACDE2" box="[784,877,702,728]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–117" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[249,1326,189,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[241,1346,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 110–117. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 110, whole fly; 111, frons; 112, detail of frons; 113, postpedicels to proboscis; 114, tergite 5 to tip of abdomen; 115, left face of epandrium; 116, left face of hypandrium and penis complex; 117, right face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573394/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 111</figureCitation>
, with without microtrichia (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFB2BA9D5A93ECDE2" box="[1191,1289,702,728]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–117" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[249,1326,189,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[241,1346,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 110–117. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 110, whole fly; 111, frons; 112, detail of frons; 113, postpedicels to proboscis; 114, tergite 5 to tip of abdomen; 115, left face of epandrium; 116, left face of hypandrium and penis complex; 117, right face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573394/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 112</figureCitation>
). Cheek with 4 bristles and jowl with 2 that are longer and more robust. Postpedicels, palps and proboscis as 
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFB33A98BA92ACDC0" box="[1215,1309,736,762]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–117" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[249,1326,189,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[241,1346,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 110–117. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 110, whole fly; 111, frons; 112, detail of frons; 113, postpedicels to proboscis; 114, tergite 5 to tip of abdomen; 115, left face of epandrium; 116, left face of hypandrium and penis complex; 117, right face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573394/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 113</figureCitation>
, the labella lacking small spinules below. Thorax brown, with 3 notopleural bristles and no cleft in front of these. Mesopleuron bare. Scutellum with an anterior pair of small hairs and a posterior pair of bristles. Abdominal tergites brown with small hairs that are longer at rear of T6 (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFDD4A82FAEC2CC64" box="[600,757,836,862]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–117" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[249,1326,189,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[241,1346,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 110–117. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 110, whole fly; 111, frons; 112, detail of frons; 113, postpedicels to proboscis; 114, tergite 5 to tip of abdomen; 115, left face of epandrium; 116, left face of hypandrium and penis complex; 117, right face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573394/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 114–117</figureCitation>
). Legs with brown to yellowish brown femora and tibiae and yellowish tarsi. Fore tarsus (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFE55A80EAE0ECC45" box="[473,569,869,895]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–121" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1027,1052]" captionTargetBox="[187,1412,369,986]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[163,1425,345,1003]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 118–121. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 118, front tarsus; 119, hind femur; 120, wing; 121, detail of wing base. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573396" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573396/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 118</figureCitation>
) with posterodorsal hair palisade on segments 1–4 and 5 about as long as 4. Dorsal hair palisade of mid tibia extends about 0.69 times its length. Hairs below basal half of hind femur clearly longer than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFD7CA8C1AF65CCFE" box="[752,850,938,964]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–121" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1027,1052]" captionTargetBox="[187,1412,369,986]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[163,1425,345,1003]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 118–121. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 118, front tarsus; 119, hind femur; 120, wing; 121, detail of wing base. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573396" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573396/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 119</figureCitation>
). Hind tibia with almost 2 dozen moderately differentiated posterodorsal hairs, without anterodorsals, and spinules of apical combs simple. Wings (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFB53A8A5A9A3CCD2" box="[1247,1428,974,1000]" captionStart="FIGURES 118–121" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1027,1052]" captionTargetBox="[187,1412,369,986]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[163,1425,345,1003]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 118–121. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 118, front tarsus; 119, hind femur; 120, wing; 121, detail of wing base. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573396" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573396/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 120 &amp; 121</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity id="FF07E4EBFF8D255AFF1BA89AACCCCB37" box="[151,251,1009,1037]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.50 mm</quantity>
long. Costal index 0.35. Costal ratios 4.65: 1.19: 1. Costal cilia (of section 3) 
<quantity id="FF07E4EBFF8D255AFBFBA899A8ECCB37" box="[1143,1243,1010,1037]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.08">0.08 mm</quantity>
long. Vein 3 hair 
<quantity id="FF07E4EBFF8D255AFF1BAF7DACCCCB0B" box="[151,251,1046,1073]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.03">0.03 mm</quantity>
long. Two unequal axillary bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity id="FF07E4EBFF8D255AFCF0AF7DAFE8CB0B" box="[892,991,1046,1073]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.11">0.11 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere knob bristles, the outermost being 
<quantity id="FF07E4EBFF8D255AFE50AF51AE09CB6F" box="[476,574,1082,1109]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" unit="mm" value="0.11">0.11 mm</quantity>
long. Sc not reaching R1. Haltere knob yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3840490EFF8D255AFF4BAF36A973CAE9" blockId="18.[151,1437,635,1563]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFF4BAF36AD6ACB42" bold="true" box="[199,349,1117,1144]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Recognition.</emphasis>
In the key to the 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFDAEAF35AEA0CB42" authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1856" box="[546,663,1118,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFDAEAF35AEA0CB42" box="[546,663,1118,1144]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Megaselia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males of the British Isles (
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF8D255AFC4FAF35A863CB42" author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[963,1108,1118,1144]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref21228" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 10 (8), 1 - 155." type="journal article" year="1989">Disney 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 252 lead 
<specimenCount id="2EF98287FF8D255AFA02AF35AC81CBA6" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="generic">
1 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFF1BAFE8AC81CBA6" authority="(Wood)" authorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[151,182,1155,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tarsalis">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFF1BAFE8AC81CBA6" box="[151,182,1155,1180]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
tarsalis (Wood), from which it is immediately distinguished by its slender front tarsus lacking rows of spinules on the basitarsus. In 
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF8D255AFE0DAFCDAE68CBFB" author="Borgmeier, T." box="[385,607,1190,1217]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="1 - 160" refId="ref20965" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1966) Revision of the North American Phorid flies. Part III. The species of the genus Megaselia, subgenus Megaselia (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 8, 1 - 160. [1965]" type="journal article" year="1966">Borgmeier’s (1966)</bibRefCitation>
key to Nearctic Group VIII it runs to couplet 10 lead 
<specimenCount id="2EF98287FF8D255AFB4FAFCDA8CFCBFA" box="[1219,1272,1190,1216]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="generic">
1 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFB55AFCCA8CFCBFA" authority="(Gimmerthal)" authorityName="Gimmerthal" baseAuthorityName="Gimmerthal" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[1241,1272,1191,1216]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bovista">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFB55AFCCA8CFCBFA" box="[1241,1272,1191,1216]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
bovista (Gimmerthal), a Palaearctic species with which he incorrectly synonymised the Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFBC1AFA0A903CBDF" authority="(Lintner)" authorityName="Lintner" baseAuthorityName="Lintner" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[1101,1332,1226,1253]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agarici">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFBC1AFA0A8F3CBDE" box="[1101,1220,1227,1252]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. agarici</emphasis>
(Lintner)
</taxonomicName>
, which it closely resembles (
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF8D255AFEE7AF85AE2CCA32" author="Robinson, W. H." box="[363,539,1262,1288]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="452 - 462" refId="ref21973" refString="Robinson, W. H. (1977) Phoridae (Diptera) associated with cultivated mushrooms in Eastern North America. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 79, 452 - 462." type="journal article" year="1977">Robinson 1977</bibRefCitation>
). The latter’s hypopygium most obviously differs from 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFB04AF84A8C9CA32" baseAuthorityName="Gimmerthal" baseAuthorityYear="1848" box="[1160,1278,1262,1288]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bovista">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFB04AF84A8C9CA32" box="[1160,1278,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. bovista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its distinctive left postero-ventral process of the epandrium (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFD5BAE79AF0DCA16" box="[727,826,1298,1324]" captionStart="FIGURE 122" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1870,1895]" captionTargetBox="[201,1386,1110,1844]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[201,1386,1110,1844]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 122. Megaselia agarici (Lintner) male. left face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573398" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573398/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 122</figureCitation>
). Our species more closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFB61AE78A953CA16" baseAuthorityName="Lintner" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[1261,1380,1299,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agarici">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFB61AE78A953CA16" box="[1261,1380,1299,1324]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. agarici</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
than other members of this complex. However it has a shorter more tapered left postero-ventral epandrial lobe (
<figureCitation id="A0C4558BFF8D255AFABCAE5FA9A7CA74" box="[1328,1424,1331,1358]" captionStart="FIGURES 110–117" captionStartId="19.[151,264,1945,1970]" captionTargetBox="[249,1326,189,1905]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[241,1346,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURES 110–117. Megaselia farshbafi n. sp. male. 110, whole fly; 111, frons; 112, detail of frons; 113, postpedicels to proboscis; 114, tergite 5 to tip of abdomen; 115, left face of epandrium; 116, left face of hypandrium and penis complex; 117, right face of hypopygium. Scale bars 20 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3573394" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3573394/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 115</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFF3AAE3DAD19CA55" baseAuthorityName="Lintner" baseAuthorityYear="1895" box="[182,302,1366,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agarici">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFF3AAE3DAD19CA55" box="[182,302,1366,1391]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. agarici</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
‘s the palps and anal tube are somewhat dusky rather than clear yellow. Two subsequently described species run to the same point in Borgmeier’s key. 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFD4FAE1CAFDDCAAA" authority="Disney (1981)" authorityName="Disney" authorityYear="1981" box="[707,1002,1398,1424]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sandhui">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFD4FAE1CAF77CAAA" box="[707,832,1398,1424]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. sandhui</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="5C6E34FFFF8D255AFCCBAE1DAFDDCAAA" author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[839,1002,1398,1424]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" pagination="509 - 512" refId="ref21142" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1981) Megaselia sandhui sp. n. (Diptera: Phoridae), a pest of cultivated mushrooms in India. Bulletin of Entomological Research, 71, 509 - 512. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0007485300008518" type="journal article" year="1981">Disney (1981)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, which is known from 
<collectingCountry id="40E8099EFF8D255AFB65AE1CA92ECAAB" box="[1257,1305,1399,1425]" name="Iran" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Iran</collectingCountry>
, is immediately recognized by the more robust hairs bordering a curious ‘pocket’ on segments 4 and 5 of the abdominal venter. 
<taxonomicName id="FFFF328DFF8D255AFF1BAED1AEBFCAEE" authority="Hartop, Brown &amp; Disney (2016)" authorityName="Hartop, Brown &amp; Disney" authorityYear="2016" box="[151,648,1465,1492]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wongae">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFF1BAED1AD23CAE9" box="[151,276,1466,1491]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. wongae</emphasis>
Hartop, Brown &amp; Disney (2016)
</taxonomicName>
has hypandrial lobes each side instead of only on the left side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="70E51A85FF8D255AFF4BAEB6AD1DC921" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3840490EFF8D255AFF4BAEB6AD1DC921" blockId="18.[151,1437,635,1563]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="0A8B951CFF8D255AFF4BAEB6AD79CACD" bold="true" box="[199,334,1501,1527]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named after Professor Reza Farshbaf Pourabad. (Professor of Department of Plant Protection, Tabriz, 
<collectingCountry id="40E8099EFF8D255AFF60AD6AAD29C921" box="[236,286,1537,1563]" name="Iran" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Iran</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
